:"1115","1114":"1114","1135":"1135","1079":"1079","1167":"1167","1145":"1145","1166":"1166","1100":"1100","after 1167":"after 1167","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Mulgrave Castle, Yorkshire, England":"Mulgrave Castle, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fossard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fozard  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Fozard","meanings":["Norman, English: relationship name from the Old French personal name  <i>Fossard</i>."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Fossard was born about 1115, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Robert Fossard I. He married Osceria of Yorkshire. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died after 1167."},"et":{"Abt 1115–after 1167":"umbes 1115–pärast 1167","1100–1164":"1100–1164","1110–1145":"1110–1145","1114–1166":"1114–1166","1115–1153":"1115–1153","1115–1167":"1115–1167","1100–Female":"1100–Surnud","–1195":"–1195","1138–1194":"1138–1194","–Female":"Surnud","1079–1135":"1079–1135","1110":"1110","1153":"1153","1164":"1164","Abt 1115":"umbes 1115","1195":"1195","1194":"1194","1138":"1138","1115":"1115","1